south-easter
Homonym Number:
Word Class:noun
Sense Number:
Definition:used specifically in various places: e.g. Picton, Canterbury
Origin:[none]
Register:
Register 2:
Domain:[none]
Region:[none]
See:cf. southerly buster
Pronunciation:
Notes:
Citations
Date: 0/0/1847
Source: Savage Life
Author: ANGAS
Vol / Page: 1/242
Edition:
Quote:  The position of the harbour of Port Nicholson, at the south-eastern entrance of Cook's Straits, is open to the heavy gales that frequently blow from that quarter in the winter season : between the high lands that rise on each side of the entrance to the harbour, the wind, at such seasons, rushes in, as through a funnel, with unrelenting fury. These `south-easters,' as they are termed [in Picton], generally continue two or three days, the storm being at its [243] height on the second day.
Notes:

Date: 5/7/1851
Source: Lyttelton Times
Author:
Vol / Page: 7
Edition:
Quote: This wind is similar to the well-known `south-easter' of New Zealand, which, here, tends up with the land, and so has a south westerly direction
Notes:  [Canterbury: see notes 2 rev. and 3.]

Date: 0/0/1866
Source: Polynesia
Author: ANGAS
Vol / Page: 110
Edition:
Quote: The position of the harbour of Port Nicholson, at the south-eastern entrance of Cook's Straits, renders it exposed to the heavy gales that at certain times blow from that quarter during the winter season. ... the wind, on such occasions, rushes in, as through a funnel, ... These `south-easters' generally last two or three days, and blow with such terrific violence that no communication can be held [111] with the shipping at anchor in the bay; ...
Notes: (Wellington)
